  ('whitney-museum-of-american-art', 'Whitney Museum of American Art', 'museum', 'The Whitney Museum of American Art is a modern and contemporary American art museum in the Meatpacking District and West Village neighborhoods of Manhattan in New York City, New York, United States. The institution was founded in 1930 by Gertrude Vanderbilt Whitney, a prominent American socialite, sculptor, and art patron after whom it is named.', NULL, 'Manhattan', 'West Village', '99 Gansevoort St, New York, NY 10014', 40.7395877, -74.0088629, 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/place-photos/AJRVUZO0LV8UlRkcZhHN_J1x5kwxx9x41v265V40p_PFtHH3dZ8cAov_bMW8Jq-1IHkDZ2fWMRSe3nXrmQ0Nz_NMFX05y8pl9oYfdY2X2KaubRNfoZdcNnunBQDDjRq8pi0kYzJz9s-JON97T9g=s4800-w800', ARRAY['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/place-photos/AJRVUZNEi3dqLI2mnuWbYbOoKSYQiQreL5LT_VeCAR3aLMhATpJI3q6fMvR0FaoiIay53akuuRttnBVKJSpr8xo-SGMbdGtp6tVngeUjW2d5gznvMF9-rFG_n4G1Z_mCvWQ_fbFFlYH5-iijwCsW_Q=s4800-w800', 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/place-photos/AJRVUZPD87UznkxXxM7ntbe9OZR2kdGoNxr3lDBu40BPk3ixJJHLXf3TU5S8SqERYtmS5W16Zhv1EpXnmGo39xZkGLdeCkEN3p0kmIz0Eb8LnTbEN_25A2qcajXx96QbKcgi9k891trNdVMPBQBZBA=s4800-w800', 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/place-photos/AJRVUZP1wF3D3cC6p7SzUG9qTywdE6CKj5rsc9PCFhc2odTzwrJvIHwiOMXZ0sBvr9r3yWnbsIY6gpS1-4w9of-MU1sZTbV_5KpVC3raHz5wLMGqu_R-iy1fr7vbZD0i_iljww_AFtO5M4eVKOtc=s4800-w800']::text[], '{"mon": [["10:00", "18:00"]], "tue": [["10:00", "18:00"]], "wed": [["10:00", "18:00"]], "thu": [["10:00", "18:00"]], "fri": [["10:00", "22:00"]], "sat": [["10:00", "18:00"]], "sun": [["10:00", "18:00"]]}'::jsonb, 'Mon 10:00–18:00; Tue 10:00–18:00; Wed 10:00–18:00; Thu 10:00–18:00; Fri 10:00–22:00; Sat 10:00–18:00; Sun 10:00–18:00', 'ChIJN3MJ6pRYwokRiXg91flSP8Y', 4.5, 14927.0, ARRAY['wheelchair']::text[], NULL, NULL, 90, '14 St (A,C,E)/8 Av (L)', 'https://www.google.com/maps/embed/v1/place?key=AIzaSyC1g4kcF24ADMnnTKrUSuvmbM1iGQ1qdGA&q=place_id:ChIJN3MJ6pRYwokRiXg91flSP8Y', 'https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=Whitney+Museum+of+American+Art&query_place_id=ChIJN3MJ6pRYwokRiXg91flSP8Y', 'https://www.whitney.org/', '+1-212-570-3600', ARRAY['art_museum', 'museum', 'indoor', 'wheelchair']::text[]),
  ('radio-city-music-hall', 'Radio City Music Hall', 'other', 'Radio City Music Hall is an entertainment venue and theater at 1260 Avenue of the Americas, within Rockefeller Center, in the Midtown Manhattan neighborhood of New York City. Nicknamed "The Showplace of the Nation", it is the headquarters for the Rockettes. Radio City Music Hall was designed by Edward Durell Stone and Donald Deskey in the Art Deco style.', 'Radio City Music Hall (also known as Radio City) is an entertainment venue and theater at 1260 Avenue of the Americas, within Rockefeller Center, in the Midtown Manhattan neighborhood of New York City. Nicknamed "The Showplace of the Nation", it is the headquarters for the Rockettes. Radio City Music Hall was designed by Edward Durell Stone and Donald Deskey in the Art Deco style.
Radio City Music Hall was built on a plot of land that was originally intended for an opera house for the Metropolitan Opera, plans for which were canceled in 1929. It opened on December 27, 1932, as part of the construction of Rockefeller Center. The 5,960-seat Music Hall was the larger of two venues built for Rockefeller Center''s "Radio City" section, the other being the RKO Roxy Theatre (later the Center Theatre); the "Radio City" name came to apply only to Radio City Music Hall. It was largely successful until the 1970s, when declining patronage nearly drove the theater to bankruptcy. Radio City was designated a New York City Landmark in May 1978, and it was restored and allowed to remain open. The theater was extensively renovated in 1999.
Radio City''s four-tiered auditorium was the world''s largest when it opened. The theater also contains a variety of art. Although Radio City was initially intended to host stage shows, within a year of its opening it was converted into a movie palace, hosting performances in a film-and-stage-spectacle format through the 1970s, and was the site of several movie premieres. By the late 20th and early 21st centuries, it primarily hosted concerts, including by leading pop and rock musicians, and live stage shows such as the Radio City Christmas Spectacular. Radio City has also hosted televised events including the Grammy Awards, Tony Awards, Daytime Emmy Awards, MTV Video Music Awards, and NFL draft, as well as university graduation ceremonies.', 'Manhattan', 'Midtown-Times Square', '1260 6th Ave, New York, NY 10020', 40.759975999999995, -73.9799772, 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/place-photos/AJRVUZMp0xdsAdD6AfHbtmfs0_7_KS_efC5zi6ULh4pAU5RSrJXN2Rg1F0i2Ygu3fRMVyFNqmpX0DXt6o7_5tEyZuuK1wOg8vFx_B4DDK3ufs_FG3dIuVNRdQs_z9xpm003gHA8Ps7iwdza_Wr1O=s4800-w800', ARRAY['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/place-photos/AJRVUZNzBDhzq4hnPfdYyVGQzDxXluGzcCWpDDHSUUVRwzgua63k5eezJ3-us1yAUMmgFavGuKYCOMDsmQNaSgcktMkJVvhBO524IGFNBkFSIrKr3zrO2Wn6N9G37OeBAxgh_8o5BNMhD2Q6ROW3=s4800-w800', 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/place-photos/AJRVUZNRGjKZKIQ_YmslXlEyPfkymk5cGcR7tUhahj4ssXW1SW_WyBDOGY_OcI8bQZp3rqbEApUNpHawVaj8XPsXetv3TDWjI8ANfFQqHKH_2j2F4hV9xeVsakxT7TiV-v3ymm2KI7iodi6HeOTo=s4800-w800', 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/place-photos/AJRVUZN3OKLttQdmuQFo3qPu_kqH0DrET6UHiBQUclXBqAGKLfBvxAuMHdFJD5I3xgjREqhh6I5iON1fw3vY4dmfySS4EQ7qzfoMTAuTqZS06FEBtn8y0VGSTKBZ_syWUZ1IAnVnbOqsgFk9etcukyvNfPwd=s4800-w800']::text[], NULL, '09:30-17:00', 'ChIJPS8b1vhYwokRldqq2YHmxJI', 4.8, 27499.0, ARRAY['wheelchair']::text[], NULL, NULL, 60, '47-50 Sts-Rockefeller Ctr (B,D,F,M)', 'https://www.google.com/maps/embed/v1/place?key=AIzaSyC1g4kcF24ADMnnTKrUSuvmbM1iGQ1qdGA&q=place_id:ChIJPS8b1vhYwokRldqq2YHmxJI', 'https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=Radio+City+Music+Hall&query_place_id=ChIJPS8b1vhYwokRldqq2YHmxJI', 'http://www.radiocity.com/', '(212) 465-6000', ARRAY['concert_hall', 'yes', 'indoor', 'wheelchair']::text[]),
  ('madison-square-garden', 'Madison Square Garden', 'other', 'Madison Square Garden, colloquially known as the Garden or by its initials MSG, is a multi-purpose indoor arena in New York City. It is located in Midtown Manhattan between Seventh and Eighth avenues from 31st to 33rd streets above Pennsylvania Station. It is the fourth venue to bear the name "Madison Square Garden"; the first two, opened in 1879 and 1890, were located on Madison Square, on East 26th Street and Madison Avenue, with the third Madison Square Garden (1925) farther uptown at Eighth Avenue and 50th Street.', 'Madison Square Garden, colloquially known as the Garden or by its initials MSG, is a multi-purpose indoor arena in New York City. It is located in Midtown Manhattan between Seventh and Eighth avenues from 31st to 33rd streets above Pennsylvania Station. It is the fourth venue to bear the name "Madison Square Garden"; the first two, opened in 1879 and 1890, were located on Madison Square, on East 26th Street and Madison Avenue, with the third Madison Square Garden (1925) farther uptown at Eighth Avenue and 50th Street.
The Garden hosts professional ice hockey, professional basketball, boxing, mixed martial arts, concerts, ice shows, circuses, professional wrestling and other forms of sports and entertainment. It is close to other midtown Manhattan landmarks, including the Empire State Building, Koreatown and Macy''s at Herald Square. It is home to the New York Rangers of the National Hockey League (NHL), the New York Knicks of the National Basketball Association (NBA) and was home to the New York Liberty of the Women''s National Basketball Association (WNBA) from 1997 to 2017.
Originally called Madison Square Garden Center, the Garden opened on February 11, 1968, on the site of the old Pennsylvania Station. It is the oldest major sporting facility in the New York metropolitan area. It is the oldest arena in the NBA and the second-oldest in the NHL, after Seattle''s Climate Pledge Arena. As of 2016, MSG is also the second-busiest music arena in the world in terms of ticket sales. Including its two major renovations in 1991 and 2013, the Garden''s total construction cost was approximately US$1.1 billion, and it has been ranked as one of the ten most expensive arena venues ever built. It is part of the Pennsylvania Plaza office and retail complex, named for the railway station. Several other operating entities related to the Garden share its name.', 'Manhattan', 'Midtown South-Flatiron-Union Square', 'New York, NY 10001', 40.7505045, -73.9934387, 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/place-photos/AJRVUZOr54D_so-UsQRecT0U9CKHEIlZzVjFlUP2rEdS2n-zHr-jduVy-KlrtiFzzaY5ra_lMYr1f5OLCz8bgQnavVr-RsBX2UVpvgfQ3UMX1-8XRjmjXQ066J1OswG-EeY6S-5vlKb0GeKxFWuY=s4800-w612', ARRAY['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/place-photos/AJRVUZOuS9XErfgWz5xDhCXh2w64hW4HcBkku_Kro7IF0DXZsh5P91N2IV60Rlo5QcKQ2_9rLQo6jYVB72eXhCYZFSiToVt5zEzV43doaUi-6wHkJIoO1Uu0xvYQiQBLRXbWdOVdwvLoRZFht9R_SQ=s4800-w550', 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/place-photos/AJRVUZNuSltiDOIJO0gV2qnoFuiiDwkRniME_F8J3Ai4SVc-xKNvfs0-JKJG6yT96EljQ8_ubczQ2RNLrr3aPi2j4bX7LvhnNzjCfW8Ixl9lCSbJGFjJTl-zcPrjwRbX3NERlFnj-2rdsoAM79M=s4800-w800', 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/place-photos/AJRVUZOsDQYRGOhrl9a4K5JeUI-cRvg-T4jHJhW7rqE49jatXYREpVxk0C95ixplWZ2j1HzoQpgrmkWvf7ljDk4VIyefsrXkrG9PNmH_MV1PhQcYE1WKNSc2JJpX_X8lRLYXr6XybWjDOD8PT2HPU2ACUB4=s4800-w800']::text[], NULL, NULL, 'ChIJhRwB-yFawokR5Phil-QQ3zM', 4.7, 34606.0, ARRAY['wheelchair_limited']::text[], NULL, NULL, 150, '34 St-Penn Station (A,C,E)', 'https://www.google.com/maps/embed/v1/place?key=AIzaSyC1g4kcF24ADMnnTKrUSuvmbM1iGQ1qdGA&q=place_id:ChIJhRwB-yFawokR5Phil-QQ3zM', 'https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=Madison+Square+Garden&query_place_id=ChIJhRwB-yFawokR5Phil-QQ3zM', 'http://www.thegarden.com/', '+1-212-465-6741', ARRAY['arena', 'attraction', 'indoor']::text[]),
  ('flatiron-building', 'Flatiron Building', 'landmark', 'The Flatiron Building is a 22-story, 307-foot-tall (93.6 m) steel-framed triangular building at 175 Fifth Avenue in the Flatiron District neighborhood of Manhattan in New York City. Designed by Daniel Burnham and Frederick P. Dinkelberg, it opened in 1902. The building sits on a triangular block formed by Fifth Avenue, Broadway, and East 22nd Street—where the building''s 87-foot (27 m) back end is located—with East 23rd Street grazing the triangle''s northern (uptown) peak. The name "Flatiron" derives from its triangular shape, which recalls that of a cast-iron clothes iron.', 'The Flatiron Building (originally the Fuller Building) is a 22-story, 307-foot-tall (93.6 m) steel-framed triangular building at 175 Fifth Avenue in the Flatiron District neighborhood of Manhattan in New York City. Designed by Daniel Burnham and Frederick P. Dinkelberg, it opened in 1902. The building sits on a triangular block formed by Fifth Avenue, Broadway, and East 22nd Street—where the building''s 87-foot (27 m) back end is located—with East 23rd Street grazing the triangle''s northern (uptown) peak. The name "Flatiron" derives from its triangular shape, which recalls that of a cast-iron clothes iron.
The Flatiron Building was developed as the headquarters of construction firm Fuller Company, which acquired the site from the Newhouse family in May 1901. Construction proceeded rapidly, and the building opened on October 1, 1902; it originally stood 285 feet (87 m) tall. In its early days, it was sometimes called "Burnham''s Folly" because of locals'' skepticism of the building''s structural integrity. The building was originally 20 floors; a "cowcatcher" retail space (a low attached building so called for its resemblance to the device on rail locomotives) and penthouse were added shortly after the building''s opening. The Fuller Company sold the building in 1925 to an investment syndicate. The Equitable Life Assurance Society took over the building after a foreclosure auction in 1933 and sold it to another syndicate in 1945. 
Helmsley-Spear managed the building for much of the late 20th century, renovating it several times. The Newmark Group started managing the building in 1997. Ownership was divided among several companies, which started renovating the building again in 2019. Jacob Garlick agreed to acquire the Flatiron Building at an auction in early 2023, but failed to pay the required deposit, and three of the four existing ownership groups took over the building. In October 2023, the building''s owners announced that it would be converted to residential condominiums; the project is planned to be complete by 2026.
The Flatiron Building''s facade is divided vertically into three sections, similarly to the components of a classical column. The three-story base is clad with limestone, while the upper stories are clad with glazed terracotta. The building''s steel frame, designed by structural engineering firm Purdy and Henderson, was intended to withstand four times the maximum wind force of the area. Called "one of the world''s most iconic skyscrapers and a…', 'Manhattan', 'Midtown South-Flatiron-Union Square', '175 5th Ave, New York, NY 10010', 40.7410605, -73.9896986, 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/place-photos/AJRVUZPGiQtgw3qCgMKJfwNK_iddLMPpF_Ft_5txHut4J8x5YxSuOfGfNLPgL56mucSbzLmUWIpaJ2taF8phjd0xr2KLUjYqpVHzE7tzHcisKPTx8i_xjlO4B3_AWXFCyXLVGIWoIXBjdkf8Aue8=s4800-w563', ARRAY['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/place-photos/AJRVUZM4BnmashquF5keX5r7P4lmltDox2CUqxeDeujX40l3OCE4oepbxGo9ITXlpmWfyWPGYbBnBKkPSzEBVqeFLPbUg2RUrKoKiMAyMp-jZ1Kr1Ysg195m5mA4cIgDJe6TuCeE3pMX9lC6xJB6sw=s4800-w800', 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/place-photos/AJRVUZOnRIpbppd4fhlrs_sYwqw2T_H-v6ORI7QyGG56zyUaJWGFbgryZKY2LN2pMr09e-9Mt710LFQ3ldntOtszfZktH3ulsLaM0AEARqNEol3mKLgPuEQZqP9wtEhrDODGxgczZZjzMPPz4kFtSw=s4800-w800', 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/place-photos/AJRVUZPLbQXY3qu73LCF18t9gbUx11C6D3AJ7vmz0BR9HwwFx0hgIwF6z8iiQ0LoFhWSi_Kt_0Wgct9vT4BuTeToOjnW3lR27sBbXUpeF2Aa-KekIFaNjW1cWR_qv4whyFOtQFgs565y30WbZDn0=s4800-w800']::text[], NULL, NULL, 'ChIJZx8c96NZwokRJklw7SVhKt4', 4.5, 15389.0, NULL, NULL, NULL, 30, '23 St (R,W)', 'https://www.google.com/maps/embed/v1/place?key=AIzaSyC1g4kcF24ADMnnTKrUSuvmbM1iGQ1qdGA&q=place_id:ChIJZx8c96NZwokRJklw7SVhKt4', 'https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=Flatiron+Building&query_place_id=ChIJZx8c96NZwokRJklw7SVhKt4', NULL, NULL, ARRAY['historical_landmark', 'attraction', 'indoor']::text[]),
  ('washington-square-park', 'Washington Square Park', 'park', 'Washington Square Park is a 9.75-acre (3.95 ha) public park in the Greenwich Village neighborhood of Lower Manhattan, New York City. It is an icon as well as a meeting place and center for cultural activity. The park is operated by the New York City Department of Parks and Recreation.', 'Washington Square Park is a 9.75-acre (3.95 ha) public park in the Greenwich Village neighborhood of Lower Manhattan, New York City. It is an icon as well as a meeting place and center for cultural activity. The park is operated by the New York City Department of Parks and Recreation (NYC Parks).
The park is an open space, dominated by the Washington Square Arch at the northern gateway to the park, with a tradition of celebrating nonconformity. The park''s fountain area has long been one of the city''s popular spots, and many of the local buildings have at one time served as homes and studios for artists. Many buildings have been built by New York University, while others have been converted from their former uses into academic and residential buildings.', 'Manhattan', 'Greenwich Village', 'New York, NY 10012', 40.7308838, -73.997332, 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/place-photos/AJRVUZN9LDQbd55k0NKorcHRaxt4GIb19SVOgGKAa5Du4R8M8OQXzq2K7UQe8klVfzGkjtfZd1Q2Bkvmr7WZ030ZuwfR4Rai0ugnkxezJ-Op0gj5XJnTcmw2MADFwrT6_sn1MknOO4DnyQSk7zGvKvwOEpYS=s4800-w800', ARRAY['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/place-photos/AJRVUZPIocVvQ4_jJofJ6nxpN-zMpiAcxRjJjJbiGuG4p8rlINimOn-x3Jmx5-Ge_2LK8cN6N4FiIkIIJgaqwn3M_sbtyX8l8MqisAfDh7NMPa97wQIVWFBut4Ed-YyKEYMqnwxSejpBSv4C_bvi=s4800-w630', 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/place-photos/AJRVUZO7Cox76LMWSiJrHsCDeQ0jzIhgWLra7xjqfj73QrP2AgTsZj0lKtICNiQqMS7_LsfpFM3VGvOsGmB3pIclfd-N9cHHtBMVV-JtVlNHW9YMkshIlkhL2YkRdeA8XYUf4lmi-FM-s4aJ0q68=s4800-w800', 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/place-photos/AJRVUZMMJIOfsS1AvRSc377y2F0VDoOJK8qs2_-UyDsdC4p4iEKcKpO7mexW2xs36UBQTG6afLDSfmx297F-KyY3mKKJT4JUqA_11kQVKBbLDuTI1QJkTl_E_KI3i-j4QPco9bWljv-UsPpXjU2Z=s4800-w800']::text[], '{"mon": [["06:00", "24:00"]], "tue": [["06:00", "24:00"]], "wed": [["06:00", "24:00"]], "thu": [["06:00", "24:00"]], "fri": [["06:00", "24:00"]], "sat": [["06:00", "24:00"]], "sun": [["06:00", "24:00"]]}'::jsonb, 'Daily 06:00–24:00', 'ChIJjX494pBZwokRGH620d9eYfo', 4.6, 32870.0, NULL, NULL, NULL, 60, 'W 4 St-Wash Sq (A,C,E,B,D,F,M)', 'https://www.google.com/maps/embed/v1/place?key=AIzaSyC1g4kcF24ADMnnTKrUSuvmbM1iGQ1qdGA&q=place_id:ChIJjX494pBZwokRGH620d9eYfo', 'https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=Washington+Square+Park&query_place_id=ChIJjX494pBZwokRGH620d9eYfo', 'https://www.nycgovparks.org/parks/washington-square-park', NULL, ARRAY['city_park', 'park', 'outdoor']::text[]),
