  ('gershwin-theatre', 'Gershwin Theatre', 'other', 'The Gershwin Theatre is a Broadway theater at 222 West 51st Street, on the second floor of the Paramount Plaza office building, in the Midtown Manhattan neighborhood of New York City, New York, United States. Opened in 1972, it is operated by the Nederlander Organization and is named after brothers George and Ira Gershwin, who wrote several Broadway musicals. The Gershwin is Broadway''s largest theater, with approximately 1,933 seats across two levels. Over the years, it has hosted musicals, dance companies, and concerts.', 'The Gershwin Theatre (originally the Uris Theatre) is a Broadway theater at 222 West 51st Street, on the second floor of the Paramount Plaza office building, in the Midtown Manhattan neighborhood of New York City, New York, United States. Opened in 1972, it is operated by the Nederlander Organization and is named after brothers George and Ira Gershwin, who wrote several Broadway musicals. The Gershwin is Broadway''s largest theater, with approximately 1,933 seats across two levels. Over the years, it has hosted musicals, dance companies, and concerts.
The Gershwin was designed by Ralph Alswang. It was one of the first theaters constructed under the Special Theater District amendment of 1967. The theater''s main entrances are from a midblock passageway that runs between 50th and 51st Streets. There are escalators leading from the ground floor to the second-story lobby and rotundas. The American Theater Hall of Fame, which contains inscriptions of the names of over 500 notable theatrical personalities, is placed within the lobby and rotundas. The Gershwin''s orchestra level, which has about 1,300 seats, is more than double the size of the mezzanine level, which has about 600 seats.
The Uris Buildings Corporation built the theater within the Uris Building, now Paramount Plaza, in the 1960s in exchange for several additional floors of office space. The Uris opened on November 28, 1972, with a performance of the musical Via Galactica. Following several flops, the theater was rented out for concerts and dance specials in the 1970s. The musicals The King and I and Sweeney Todd had relatively long runs at the end of the decade. The theater was renamed the Gershwin during the 37th Tony Awards in 1983, the first of six Tony Awards ceremonies to be hosted there. In the 1980s, the theater hosted concerts; its first straight plays; and musicals such as Singin'' in the Rain and Starlight Express. The theater continued to host concert appearances in the early 1990s, as well as musicals such as Show Boat, and was renovated in 1993. The Gershwin has staged the musical Wicked since 2003.', 'Manhattan', 'Midtown-Times Square', '222 W 51st St, New York, NY 10019, USA', 40.762547, -73.9849697, 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/place-photos/AJRVUZPqjXKCmXimKwYvQXRLAcpjXeDwDREFYbyxRorGxQjXlfzCUlbGNzP5y-xevtnjVwKBtZKY05sz4ljEh8nz6mqWZk9ikO228-QD-EI0qxmQOMiZfEqHaYB799D6AUrG11Ae9uAYtrrl0-bHmg=s4800-w800', ARRAY['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/place-photos/AJRVUZPqms9GNqFW61MmrsfdBeT9C8RH438IEzo_tFciPV3djncSuJrGsFVtJaapqd3KfsAgL84WQaolloWUOFlOW1P8GvmM_CRYMkGfuBxyBJBxyyYWaClTRar8AHNLTTCaEdP4t93nWTBtWOGj=s4800-w800', 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/place-photos/AJRVUZO3Ey_ECsg5D1jx03QmWukCFSwTa3rlD4Qu4lPGaay_44Xbs4ZWgbf2fPnENE7cLOEGm9hDXGBBbhI0xob_Hmgsr0FS-be2rdrnXqQPujAAbOTbBX4dP4-qA0DB-WwimKOWy1OG55EHS2KW=s4800-w800', 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/place-photos/AJRVUZOoROOVtoug_cqtPVb3YaEsjV2ea-Gmw5bFqF0fU85HhB6maOplTAXTUrh4HbJ6f2wPNrd9EAcpBZ1u_zdH7UQdjMrSgqs5_nACMgTiHazu3-dnbWCNq9hpNzDFonhYkmASglryCMMj1UJyyXWt9sfo=s4800-w800']::text[], '{"mon": [["10:00", "20:00"]], "tue": [["10:00", "20:00"]], "wed": [["10:00", "20:00"]], "thu": [["10:00", "20:00"]], "fri