  ('the-great-lawn', 'The Great Lawn', 'park', 'The Great Lawn and Turtle Pond are two connected features of Central Park in Manhattan, New York City, United States. The lawn and pond are located on the site of a former reservoir for the Croton Aqueduct system which was infilled during the early 20th century.', 'The Great Lawn and Turtle Pond are two connected features of Central Park in Manhattan, New York City, United States. The lawn and pond are located on the site of a former reservoir for the Croton Aqueduct system which was infilled during the early 20th century.
The pond, originally known as Belvedere Lake, abuts Belvedere Castle as well as the Delacorte Theater, and contains a variety of turtles and fish. The lawn is composed of 14 acres (5.7 ha) of oval-shaped land, which is used for sports and concerts.', 'Manhattan', 'Central Park', '79th Street & 85th Street, New York, NY 10024, USA', 40.7816915, -73.96641919999999, 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/place-photos/AJRVUZOvsn-jXKbnWqMnzUFsn8y_xoq9ik5iXDI1JLQpqoZzj2VwH8PADYQD0-_hBqZ4t25i-fH8R-o7AVshosKiCXNsuU3yo0hGl96puYK1o9wTj6gE6rUHau-1wHB67HKUUj6YpT99tT8sUF_xAAE7lMcG=s4800-w800', ARRAY['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/place-photos/AJRVUZPIzl9QvMJA_M1MjPDY2O4_Ng9h0DXf3KAyDYCv0ggpUAbVpsvv-aAmMzjztQp2cnyidjFjoZQU1i2e7xQs9Czj1pC4bvisngH6Jm5ReGAJhAbYr8lILJxvv7nxB-B-yzTVK9-qAC2fHRE=s4800-w800', 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/place-photos/AJRVUZOjtJ-dbX-UhTYZN3X9W8P9G0k7oWjtVev7-LeCQqWhyQY9J-iCEEhuogj-NKbHz2KHLZDqD58FVxiVN974kFCfqN-8Y_XVbKIDNLNKU4mXn98oFFHZkIprbGQR1KH0hG3E39bYVyccv9nJ=s4800-w800', 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/place-photos/AJRVUZPj9EIqGHqVTw3G5vjjWJpFwl0LMz3SamUlvq_nHUnmECF9zSRiWWGdFpXHZRXs_c1-diFm8TF0DWzfXy54r4qDxhxFamLweyNnQosH_vn9f5YHh3SGSrhWBAtklojQHQHCKdv2OImv-GQ1xA=s4800-w800']::text[], '{"mon": [["06:00", "01:00"]], "tue": [["06:00", "01:00"]], "wed": [["06:00", "01:00"]], "thu": [["06:00", "01:00"]], "fri": [["06:00", "01:00"]], "sat": [["06:00", "01:00"]], "sun": [["06:00", "01:00"]]}'::jsonb, 'Daily 06:00–01:00', 'ChIJd7iQrJBYwokROrpPbxeQsUc', 4.8, 2080.0, NULL, NULL, NULL, 60, '81 St-Museum of Natural History (C,B)', 'https://www.google.com/maps/embed/v1/place?key=AIzaSyC1g4kcF24ADMnnTKrUSuvmbM1iGQ1qdGA&q=place_id:ChIJd7iQrJBYwokROrpPbxeQsUc', 'https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=The+Great+Lawn&query_place_id=ChIJd7iQrJBYwokROrpPbxeQsUc', 'https://www.centralparknyc.org/locations/great-lawn', '(212) 310-6600', ARRAY['park', 'pitch', 'outdoor']::text[]),
  ('gerald-schoenfeld-theatre', 'Gerald Schoenfeld Theatre', 'other', 'The Gerald Schoenfeld Theatre is a Broadway theater at 236 West 45th Street in the Theater District of Midtown Manhattan in New York City, New York, U.S. Opened in 1917, the theater was designed by Herbert J. Krapp and was built for the Shubert brothers. The Schoenfeld Theatre is named for Gerald Schoenfeld, longtime president of the Shubert Organization, which operates the theater. It has 1,079 seats across two levels. Both the facade and the auditorium interior are New York City landmarks.', 'The Gerald Schoenfeld Theatre (known as the Plymouth Theatre prior to 2004) is a Broadway theater at 236 West 45th Street in the Theater District of Midtown Manhattan in New York City, New York, U.S. Opened in 1917, the theater was designed by Herbert J. Krapp and was built for the Shubert brothers. The Schoenfeld Theatre is named for Gerald Schoenfeld, longtime president of the Shubert Organization, which operates the theater. It has 1,079 seats across two levels. Both the facade and the auditorium interior are New York City landmarks.
The neoclassical facade is simple in design and is similar to that of the Broadhurst Theatre, which was developed concurrently. The Schoenfeld''s facade is made of buff-colored brick and terracotta and is divided into two sections: a stage house to the west and the theater''s entrance to the east. The entrance facade is topped by fire-escape galleries and contains a curved corner facing east toward Broadway. The auditorium contains an orchestra level, a large balcony, a small technical gallery, a mostly flat ceiling, and a sounding board. The space is decorated in the Adam style with plasterwork designs. Near the front of the auditorium, flanking the elliptical proscenium arch, are box seats at balcony level.
The Shubert brothers developed the Broadhurst and Plymouth theaters following the success of the Booth and Shubert theaters directly to the east. The Plymouth Theatre was leased to Arthur Hopkins and opened on October 10, 1917, with the comedy A Successful Calamity. The Shuberts retained ownership of the theater and took over after Hopkins''s death in 1950. The theater has hosted not only musicals but also revues, comedies, and dramas throughout its history. It was renamed for Gerald Schoenfeld in 2005.', 'Manhattan', 'Midtown-Times Square', '236 W 45th St, New York, NY 10036, USA', 40.7586139, -73.9873111, 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/place-photos/AJRVUZNGLK6e1aDBalfDxSTrBRb3ncoQisH3-18aDVPqpRfD_LI3JmaBl-FkFgfVyNKuY5FtFVuezARomXhFFzFsj9D8B9Jdo7V0zEm6u3XZkw4qOxJ-MPObLkPNjf6O8CfOjf2F2vCe3gdBB1Y=s4800-w800', ARRAY['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/place-photos/AJRVUZP2rki0V6zFMWOD0OGaS4ICoIpJg6HJTLolEgJ8biVH1BiIfOj4hy8s2JNpm15tpLcmuLJ50dAaHEl8kkZgon9Q5xnqD2xExKelO_-NCqW4JE7ann279MyT_kmGymxPhhdrokY74epW_H8=s4800-w800', 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/place-photos/AJRVUZNaW_WNrwEAMOD_IaLEwbfw5zE89b_Pa2qcV9a9gede5UN3DwGBeWO5URVy4M0ykoKxImtUiLdRk61C-OqVyaS7Tdv89D8PHzTdmPa52iy1XgETHTWS4T8Amc5S6zOxOSI0TuCfU7SVZl2UteqDufpw=s4800-w800', 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/place-photos/AJRVUZP2HdGp9_3u4xzQdIuJsB5kyd92HR82olWJmK9nnGJDUIku5FwP1vLdXcrUhaF3WMC_kmqZKMZ0hzlCcOnDbe6szzCE7s1IbaRr9a7pEjUxlzglO7LQotV14snE6iGHXn_zCJCGjnSrIi0Exq5hN8pm=s4800-w800']::text[], NULL, NULL, 'ChIJiWtLIFZYwokRGiU3LaSBgMc', 4.7, 2025.0, ARRAY['wheelchair']::text[], NULL, NULL, 120, 'Times Sq-42 St (N,Q,R,W,S,1,2,3,7)/42 St (A,C,E)', 'https://www.google.com/maps/embed/v1/place?key=AIzaSyC1g4kcF24ADMnnTKrUSuvmbM1iGQ1qdGA&q=place_id:ChIJiWtLIFZYwokRGiU3LaSBgMc', 'https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=Gerald+Schoenfeld+Theatre&query_place_id=ChIJiWtLIFZYwokRGiU3LaSBgMc', 'https://shubert.nyc/theatres/gerald-schoenfeld/', '(212) 239-6200', ARRAY['performing_arts_theater', 'theatre', 'indoor', 'wheelchair']::text[]),
  ('astor-place-theatre', 'Astor Place Theatre', 'other', NULL, NULL, 'Manhattan', 'Greenwich Village', '434 Lafayette St, New York, NY 10003, USA', 40.7293234, -73.9922112, 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/place-photos/AJRVUZNAUiYxSOn2Yas0lyZwLA3_BEa6X-NM1pbYUeQwhemGJpeMzb268n0AJjdlSadjY7XQj6CRdYqPrh1dZuw-iklMsVjoTuEPIX9slUw2aQ4dHwLq2ugdpISozB1gSf5tjnGKiYnByjQdZIISt7yheiw=s4800-w800', ARRAY['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/place-photos/AJRVUZNChD5IYCq5ubNdS7lgGjaD4lK29rL5ws5oXZU7_AOLYkAO6KtyA9NoWAK7BDqH2UnuCYzGx5ylHuoMqM9SZ82TtXTq8uC43_KmpBhC6lk9O7A5LsHu5dzPnOTVkbQ8XsMK3atM4vxrJo6l=s4800-w800', 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/place-photos/AJRVUZM5ZuocdrD__hlbktbVOufenyjYixliE3XbRdkeoKBSVxncFKPR64pO7w_MxfBEDvRgAw9XFoRU206bDDat91fMu0BAqYpo5SMBrI6odz013DQW14XDwLzQL4MAc40QZlJY9otgpyofaqnC=s4800-w800', 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/place-photos/AJRVUZO2HMNjhqbprMgX3xhdcaoMQMGD-O2mlr1AWIYeEpEKNZs1ySXK8sZSy74-zxXiTXdoDudqaUPBQU_il3oIQ_c_T7SxA3M43ZblzMJ7dybpOy8HgH8DyXDPulCq2ZVmJXjJAKKTSPHO3ylRJQ=s4800-w800']::text[], '{"mon": [["18:00", "22:00"]], "tue": null, "wed": null, "thu": [["16:00", "22:00"]], "fri": [["18:00", "22:00"]], "sat": [["14:00", "22:00"]], "sun": [["14:00", "22:00"]]}'::jsonb, 'Mon 18:00–22:00; Thu 16:00–22:00; Fri 18:00–22:00; Sat 14:00–22:00; Sun 14:00–22:00', 'ChIJYV33VZpZwokRRxMtftbR_Lg', 4.5, 1978.0, NULL, NULL, NULL, 120, '8 St-NYU (R,W)', 'https://www.google.com/maps/embed/v1/place?key=AIzaSyC1g4kcF24ADMnnTKrUSuvmbM1iGQ1qdGA&q=place_id:ChIJYV33VZpZwokRRxMtftbR_Lg', 'https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=Astor+Place+Theatre&query_place_id=ChIJYV33VZpZwokRRxMtftbR_Lg', 'https://www.blueman.com/new-york/about-show', '(917) 695-9330', ARRAY['performing_arts_theater', 'theatre', 'indoor']::text[]),
  ('metlife-building', 'MetLife Building', 'other', 'The MetLife Building is a skyscraper at Park Avenue and 45th Street, north of Grand Central Terminal, in the Midtown Manhattan neighborhood of New York City, New York, U.S. Designed in the International style by Richard Roth, Walter Gropius, and Pietro Belluschi and completed in 1962, the MetLife Building is 808 feet (246 m) tall with 59 stories. It was advertised as the world''s largest commercial office space by square footage at its opening, with 2.4 million square feet (220,000 m2) of usable office space. As of November 2022, the MetLife Building remains one of the 100 tallest buildings in the United States.', 'The MetLife Building (also 200 Park Avenue and formerly the Pan Am Building) is a skyscraper at Park Avenue and 45th Street, north of Grand Central Terminal, in the Midtown Manhattan neighborhood of New York City, New York, U.S. Designed in the International style by Richard Roth, Walter Gropius, and Pietro Belluschi and completed in 1962, the MetLife Building is 808 feet (246 m) tall with 59 stories. It was advertised as the world''s largest commercial office space by square footage at its opening, with 2.4 million square feet (220,000 m2) of usable office space. As of November 2022, the MetLife Building remains one of the 100 tallest buildings in the United States.
The MetLife Building contains an elongated octagonal massing with the longer axis perpendicular to Park Avenue. The building sits atop two levels of railroad tracks leading into Grand Central Terminal. The facade is one of the first precast concrete exterior walls in a building in New York City. In the lobby is a pedestrian passage to Grand Central''s Main Concourse, a lobby with artwork, and a parking garage at the building''s base. A rooftop heliport operated in the 1960s and briefly in 1977. The MetLife Building''s design has been widely criticized since it was proposed, largely due to its location next to Grand Central Terminal.
A skyscraper on the site of Grand Central Terminal was first proposed in 1954 to raise money for the New York Central Railroad and New York, New Haven and Hartford Railroad, the financially struggling railroads that operated the terminal. Subsequently, plans were announced for what later became the MetLife Building, to be built behind the terminal rather than in place of it. Work on the project, initially known as Grand Central City, started in 1959 and the building was formally opened on March 7, 1963. At its opening, the building was named for Pan American World Airways, for which it served as headquarters. The Metropolitan Life Insurance Company (MetLife) bought the Pan Am Building in 1981 and used it as their headquarters before selling the building in 2005. The MetLife Building has been renovated several times, including in the mid-1980s, early 2000s, and late 2010s.', 'Manhattan', 'East Midtown-Turtle Bay', '200 Park Ave, New York, NY 10166, USA', 40.7535178, -73.9767512, 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/place-photos/AJRVUZMJqN-k-x_OR8Uc_fEHT4E0G2PXN6QlzxONg9roWwxM24S5H5QL55rjhsVU9dl0VKTdnXj8fXqEegyy8cQMANOEQaVk22V4BkN4jNdGaN2BoNcpoTEb_bPirXrvECUxnedKy__S-ej9bAAu=s4800-w800', ARRAY['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/place-photos/AJRVUZOLDeqEb76Xkn9POzokXx-BL6hDDjF75E0q3mJD3_gIwo1odOsT-pd1f_urgr1mo6O0GeH3WUeHpzfU9mrNalcasrTaobbqYxVynvXdch2eaGYwjvCr4XvUdzYaiE9ELyT8bFoa5k0EBjFL=s4800-w800', 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/place-photos/AJRVUZNGNsi3XinBC-wxGergTFtZnO50Ze9xTGZe8yD6qpzvg_Cft3L_zpBjWzQFeH49NZIL5KeIdS2ndTJr_nccy9GUXQH1pv7fRhW7Xn6sBZH2bMMGbzITPkmdvpVnnw_IhP7kuq-a5_T3-LpbUA=s4800-w800', 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/place-photos/AJRVUZNj3zZMp4X5kfc2XQtb23JbXMA4UWGDJx28fxyerRIfXjLAQ9WETR1ZLc5kCMeJhvB3mgZVfLezt1Nwu-spXuNGTCJz6WN4gN-VzbQqNX_47pofFEt94xjn6O4BrXDAeNsrQKFQcQ8GMMwy=s4800-w800']::text[], NULL, NULL, 'ChIJhZJ3Yq5ZwokRop0t2AA2eWk', 4.5, 1935.0, NULL, NULL, NULL, 60, 'Grand Central-42 St (S,4,5,6,7)', 'https://www.google.com/maps/embed/v1/place?key=AIzaSyC1g4kcF24ADMnnTKrUSuvmbM1iGQ1qdGA&q=place_id:ChIJhZJ3Yq5ZwokRop0t2AA2eWk', 'https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=MetLife+Building&query_place_id=ChIJhZJ3Yq5ZwokRop0t2AA2eWk', 'http://www.tishmanspeyer.com/properties/Property.aspx?id=57', NULL, ARRAY['corporate_office', 'indoor']::text[]),
